		<img width="2500" height="1201" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-canada-jays.jpg" class="singlepostthumb wp-post-image" alt="closeup of a Canada jay" decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-canada-jays.jpg 2500w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-canada-jays-520x250.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-canada-jays-768x369.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-canada-jays-1200x576.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-canada-jays-1536x738.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-canada-jays-2048x984.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-canada-jays-900x432.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 2500px) 100vw, 2500px" /><div class="post-thumbnail-caption">Canada jays, of the Pacific type, are found in subalpine forests along the Coast Mountains and the Cascade Range from Northern California to British Columbia. They are a gregarious species, easily spotted if hiking, skiing, or snowshoeing the back country. Photo by Mike Hubert/Shutterstock</div>
			<article class="main container col4">
								<header class="maincol">
										<h1 class="pagetitle">The Naturalist and the Wonderful, Lovable, So Good, Very Bold Jay</h1>
										<h2 class="dek singlepagecontainer">Canada jays thrive in the cold. The life’s work of one biologist gives us clues as to how they’ll fare in a hotter world.</h2>
										<section class="singlebyline singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Authored by</h3>
						by  
										<a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/profiles/brian-payton/" class="tagmanager" id="author_link_top" >Brian Payton</a>								<br/>
												</section>
					 
					<aside class="singlebydatewords singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Wordcount</h3>
						November 14, 2023 | 3,700 words, about 18 minutes					</aside>
				</header>

